04300nam a22005655i 9780822379737DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19911992ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223797377 a10.1515/97808223797372doi  a(DE-B1597)554386  a(OCoLC)1226678471  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPL2265b.W28 1992 7aLIT0080002bisacsh04a895.1/092201 aWang, Jing, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Story of Stone :bIntertextuality, Ancient Chinese Stone Lore, and the Stone Symbolism in ‹i›Dream of the Red Chamber‹/i›, ‹i›Water Margin‹/i›, and ‹i›The Journey to the West‹/i› /cJing Wang. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1991] 4c©1992  a1 online resource (360 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPost-Contemporary Interventions00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Intertextuality and Interpretation -- t2. The Mythological Dictionary of Stone -- t3. Stone and Jade: From the Fictitious to the Morally Prescribed -- t4. The Story of Stone: The Problematic of Contradiction and Constraint -- t5. The Paradox of Desire and Emptiness: The Stone Monkey Intertextualized -- t6. The Inscribed Stone Tablet -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this pathbreaking study of three of the most familiar texts in the Chinese tradition-all concerning stones endowed with magical properties-Jing Wang develops a monumental reconstruction of ancient Chinese stone lore. Wang's thorough and systematic comparison of these classic works illuminates the various tellings of the stone story and provides new insight into major topics in traditional Chinese literature.Bringing together Chinese myth, religion, folklore, art, and literature, this book is the first in any language to amass the sources of stone myth and stone lore in Chinese culture. Uniting classical Chinese studies with contemporary Western theoretical concerns, Wang examines these stone narratives by analyzing intertextuality within Chinese traditions. She offers revelatory interpretations to long-standing critical issues, such as the paradoxical character of the monkey in The Journey to the West, the circularity of narrative logic in The Dream of the Red Chamber, and the structural necessity of the stone tablet in Water Margin.By both challenging and incorporating traditional sinological scholarship, Wang's The Story of Stone reveals the ideological ramifications of these three literary works on Chinese cultural history and makes the past relevant to contemporary intellectual discourse. Specialists in Chinese literature and culture, comparative literature, literary theory, and religious studies will find much of interest in this outstanding work, which is sure to become a standard reference on the subject.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aChinese literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aStone in literature. 0aStonexFolklore. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822379737zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822379737423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822379737.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles